			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Jhinrae heard the raw pain in the older woman's voice and knew that this story would be excruciating for her to tell, but for some reason, she needed to hear it, needed her answers.  Almost hesistantly, Jhinrae asked, "Three daughters and your husband all for the sake of His will? I do naut understand what you mean."
<br />

<br />
A frown furrowed her brow as she spoke further, "You asked how familiar I was with our origins, sadly I am naut. I understand Him feeding on our hatred to further his own, but I do naut understand why he would force you to sacrifice your family for His will."
<br />

<br />
She waited for her answers, scarcely daring to breathe.  She did not wait long.
<br />

<br />
"I can see myself in you dalharil. I was as young once, I think. Perhaps even more naive, because I had the delusion that I was a woman of the world and that I knew our Father and what He would want of His Children. I still thought of Him as a Father who protects and cares for His offspring." The laugh she gave sounded almost genuinely amused. "What a little wael I was."
<br />

<br />
She pulled her knees up to her chest and wrapped her arms around them, her short locks tousled and spiky from her swim. Suddenly the woman with the attitude and bearing of a queen looked like a lost child. "I came from humble origins, nau noble qu'ellar or name for me. The first ellar I joined was Undraeth. It was shaky though, and intrigue started to erode its crumbling foundation. But there I met my husband, Zaknyfein. He was someone I would have sworn would never look twice at me, I had naut even risen to the 16th rank in the Dead before he asked for my hand in marriage, he was a seasoned warrior, brave and strong. Gentle. Loving." Her eyes were focused on something only she could see. "He did naut Hate, but then neither did I, naut then. I only thought I did. There is a difference, you know.
<br />

<br />
"And we had a child, a daughter, and named her Zarynne. And as she started growing, wonderful things started to happen to me. I was named an elder in Undraeth. I became someone that people looked up to. I had gained skill and renown in armor crafting as well, and that followed me to my next qu'ellar, Veldrin, after Undraeth finally collapsed. Suddenly it seemed that this small unimportant jalil had Innoruuk's favor, and it was a heady idea to be sure. I was nearly drunk on the power.
<br />

<br />
"And from the fall of Veldrin was born Qu'ellar V'Umbra. I was second in charge there. I negotiated treaties with the other qu'ellaren. I officiated at ceremonies. Eventually I became Ilharess. And through it all, I felt Innoruuk's favor. I didn't realize what I was sacrificing though. First my husband. I never saw him, I was always too busy. And he did naut believe. He was an "embarrassment". He was friends with pales. He spoke openly of love. And so, ever mindful of my "position", I divorced him. That act separated Zarynne and I as well. She never spoke to me again. Soon after, she disappeared."
<br />

<br />
The words were spoken calmly, flatly, without any depth or tone to them at all, but her eyes shone bright with remembered pain. She took a deep breath, nerving herself up to continue. "Well, they say confession is good for the soul, do they naut, dalharil?"<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738273" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v701/evileene/evilsig2.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Evileene Diablerie on Wed Feb 02, 2005 2:19 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
