			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Eve watched as the child's compassion warred with her curiousity.  Jhinrae started to recant her desire to learn, but by now, Eve knew she had to tell someone her story.. it might as well be this jalil, who reminded her of herself so many years ago.
<br />

<br />
Eve smiled tremulously at the jalil, shaking her head gently. "Nau, dalharil. This is something you may as well understand sooner rather than later. Even those who have His favor, He plots against. If we became too happy, too complacent, our Hate lessens, and He feeds on it, He needs it. Do naut confer the qualities of a pale god on the Father. He cares only for our use to Him, naut us as flesh and blood, or souls. And if one lets pride or arrogance grow too strong, the price will be all the more. Sometimes more than can be born."
<br />

<br />
The air around them almost seemed to stop moving, utter silence, as if the walls themselves were listening to her story. She shifted slightly, the rough stone beneath her digging into tender flesh hardly protected by the thin swatch of fabric she had swaddled herself in. Here, in this place, she could almost smell Innoruuk. The hate and malice were thick here, like a fog, they seeped from the walls, and rose like tendrils from the cobblestone streets. She raised an imaginary glass in salute to him, knowing the child before her probably though she was stark raving mad. Of course, that might not be far from the case.
<br />

<br />
"I loved my new title and new station. Tier'dal bowing and kneeling to me. My name known throughout Neriak, and even through parts of the other cities. The adulation, the power.. it even convinced me I did naut miss my family so much. I did naut need them. I was Ilharess. Like I said earlier, dalharil. I was a wael.
<br />

<br />
"And then I started getting vengeful. The power I had? Anyone who had ever wronged me, I could even the score now. I seduced a jaluk. A married jaluk. His wife had tried to steal my husband, so I set out to steal hers. I enjoyed his company in my bed, but I was using him. And breaking a trust, for his wife was a member of my own qu'ellar. And I became pregnant for the second time. So rare for our people. We are naut a fertile lot. In my spite, I told him of the child, and then told him he would never get to see it, hold it, have anything to do with it. I knew that would destroy him, you see, for he doted on his other children.
<br />

<br />
"The birth of my daughter softened me, though. She was so perfect, a gift in every way. Kieryn was a delight to me. And so I relented, and gave Kerath... yes, I know you know the name.. a place in her life. Until the day the soldiers came..."</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
